\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now,
 compute the products 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\alpha}D_{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\beta}D_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

.
 
\shape italic
Reinterpret the resulting matrix as the matrix of a single rotation.
 
\shape default
Do the results make sense in terms of your answers in part (a)?
 Recall the trigonometric identities
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather*}
\sin(\alpha\pm\beta)=\sin\alpha\cos\beta\pm\cos\alpha\sin\beta\\
\cos(\alpha\pm\beta)=\cos\alpha\cos\beta\mp\sin\alpha\sin\beta.
\end{gather*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Exercise*

\shape italic
NB:
 This exercise could be reinterpreted as a 
\emph on
proof
\emph default
 of these trigonometric identities!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(a) The first transformation rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

,
 and then by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

,
 resulting in the transformation that rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 through the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The second transformation rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 through an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and then by an angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

,
 resulting in the same transformation that rotates 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 through the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta$
\end_inset

.
 So yes,
 they are the same.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset

(b) We first multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\alpha}D_{\beta}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{\alpha}D_{\beta} & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\alpha & -\sin\alpha\\
\sin\alpha & \cos\alpha
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\beta & -\sin\beta\\
\sin\beta & \cos\beta
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\alpha\cos\beta-\sin\alpha\sin\beta & -\cos\alpha\sin\beta-\sin\alpha\cos\beta\\
\sin\alpha\cos\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta & -\sin\alpha\sin\beta+\cos\alpha\sin\beta
\end{bmatrix}\\
\text{(by the trig identities)} & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos(\alpha+\beta) & -\sin(\alpha+\beta)\\
\sin(\alpha+\beta) & \cos(\alpha+\beta)
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
This last matrix we recognize as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\alpha+\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\alpha}D_{\beta}=D_{\alpha+\beta}$
\end_inset

,
 which makes perfect sense in light of the interpretation of part (a).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Performing the same computation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 swapped,
 we would obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{\beta}D_{\alpha}=D_{\beta+\alpha}$
\end_inset

,
 which is the same because 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha+\beta=\beta+\alpha$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
D_{\alpha}D_{\beta}=D_{\beta}D_{\alpha}=D_{\alpha+\beta},
\]

\end_inset

which is just re-stating what we said in (a) using matrix language.
\end_layout

